# DTLS Finished Receive Sequence Bookkeeping Is Partially Equivalent

## Summary

wolfSSL implements the normal DTLS receive-side handshake sequencing model for ordinary handshake messages: future messages are queued, old messages are skipped, and in-order complete messages are processed. The generic successful-message counter update explicitly excludes `finished`, so a successfully processed DTLS 1.2 Finished message does not advance `dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number` in the same way as other handshake messages.

This is best classified as a partial equivalence rather than a proven packet-level failure. wolfSSL covers the main external effects through Finished-specific state (`got_finished`), epoch/change-cipher checks, retransmission handling, and handshake-completion reset paths. What is not equivalent is the strict RFC bookkeeping model where every accepted handshake message, including Finished, advances the notional receive sequence counter before later duplicates become old messages.

## Standard Requirement

Official standard: [RFC 6347](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6347)

Relevant section: `4.2.2 Handshake Message Format`

Short original English excerpt from the standard:

```text
DTLS implementations maintain (at least notionally) a next_receive_seq counter.
next_receive_seq is incremented and the message is processed.
```

The surrounding paragraph describes a receive-side `next_receive_seq` counter: equal sequence numbers are accepted and advance the counter, lower sequence numbers are discarded, and greater sequence numbers may be queued or discarded. The phrase "at least notionally" means an implementation does not need this exact internal variable, but it does need equivalent receive-order behavior. RFC 6347 lists `finished` as a handshake message type and does not carve it out from this receive sequencing rule.

## Relevant Source Code

`src/internal.c:19554` checks receive-side handshake ordering before dispatch:

```c
if (ssl->keys.dtls_peer_handshake_number >
        ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number &&
        ...
        !ignoreFinished) {
    ...
    DtlsMsgStore(ssl, ssl->keys.curEpoch,
                 ssl->keys.dtls_peer_handshake_number,
                 input + *inOutIdx, size, type,
                 fragOffset, fragSz, ssl->heap);
```

Greater-than-expected messages are stored for later processing.

`src/internal.c:19623` skips old or already processed messages:

```c
else if (ssl->keys.dtls_peer_handshake_number <
            ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number ||
        ...
        ignoreFinished) {
    WOLFSSL_MSG("Already saw this message and processed it");
    *inOutIdx += fragSz;
```

Less-than-expected messages are not dispatched to the handshake-message handler.

`src/internal.c:19678` processes an in-order complete message:

```c
else {
    WOLFSSL_MSG("Branch is in order and a complete message");
    ...
    ret = DoHandShakeMsgType(ssl, input, inOutIdx, type, size, totalSz);
```

This is the positive path for `message_seq == dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number`.

`src/internal.c:18779` updates the expected receive-side handshake number after successful message handling:

```c
if (ret == 0) {
    if (type == client_hello) {
        if (ssl->msgsReceived.got_client_hello)
            ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number =
                ssl->keys.dtls_peer_handshake_number + 1;
    }
    else if (type != finished) {
        ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number++;
    }
}
```

The generic increment path explicitly excludes `finished`.

`src/internal.c:18305`, `src/internal.c:17822`, and `src/internal.c:24947` provide Finished-specific protection and reset behavior:

```c
case finished:
    if (ssl->msgsReceived.got_finished) {
        WOLFSSL_MSG("Duplicate Finished received");
        return DUPLICATE_MSG_E;
    }
    ...
    ssl->msgsReceived.got_finished = 1;
```

```c
if (ssl->options.dtls) {
    ...
    DtlsMsgPoolReset(ssl);
    ssl->keys.dtls_handshake_number = 0;
    ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number = 0;
}
```

```c
if ((!ssl->options.resuming &&
        ssl->options.side == WOLFSSL_SERVER_END) ||
    (ssl->options.resuming &&
        ssl->options.side == WOLFSSL_CLIENT_END)) {
    ssl->keys.dtls_handshake_number = 0;
    ssl->keys.dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number = 0;
}
```

## Implementation Behavior

Equivalent or near-equivalent behavior:

- future handshake messages are stored with `DtlsMsgStore`;
- old handshake messages are skipped instead of processed again;
- equal, complete ordinary handshake messages are processed;
- successful ordinary messages advance `dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number`;
- duplicate Finished messages are rejected by Finished-specific state;
- handshake completion resets DTLS handshake counters for the next handshake phase.

Non-equivalent bookkeeping:

- successful Finished processing does not directly increment `dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number`; it is excluded by `type != finished`;
- a repeated Finished is therefore not classified as old solely because `message_seq < next_receive_seq`; wolfSSL must rely on Finished-specific duplicate checks or later reset/ignore paths.

## Inconsistency Reason

The standard describes a notional per-message receive counter that advances when the received message sequence equals the expected sequence. wolfSSL follows this model for ordinary handshake messages, but uses a special Finished lifecycle instead of advancing the same counter for Finished. That means wolfSSL can be behaviorally equivalent for common Finished handling, but it is not a strict one-to-one implementation of the RFC's receive-sequence bookkeeping rule.

The concrete mismatch is narrow: after an in-order Finished is accepted and `DoFinished()` succeeds, `DoHandShakeMsgType()` returns through the `type != finished` exclusion without setting `dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number` to the next value. A strict `next_receive_seq` model would have advanced the expected receive sequence at that point.

## Runtime Evidence

Focused verification script: `verify_wolfssl_dtls12_051_098.py`

Execution log: `verify_wolfssl_dtls12_051_098.log`

The script passed checks for future-message queueing, old-message skipping, in-order dispatch, ordinary-message increment, Finished exclusion, Finished duplicate/reset fallback, and evidence line validity. This confirms the static source-code shape described above; it does not prove a packet-level interoperability failure.

Packet-level runtime note: `runtime_blocker_051_098.md` records why a DTLS packet reproducer could not be run from the existing build without reconfiguring and instrumenting the target.

## Impact

The practical risk is limited unless a retransmission or renegotiation edge case depends on the receive-sequence counter having advanced immediately after Finished. Finished has additional semantic checks and occurs at the end of the handshake flight, so duplicate handling and handshake reset reduce exposure. The remaining confirmed concern is specification traceability: the generic receive-sequence counter does not show that every accepted handshake message, including Finished, advances `next_receive_seq` exactly as written.

## Fix Direction

Consider making Finished bookkeeping explicit. One low-risk direction is to document the Finished exception next to the `type != finished` branch and prove with focused tests that all Finished paths either advance an equivalent state or reset/ignore the receive sequence only after no further message in the same handshake can be accepted. If strict RFC traceability is desired, update the Finished success path to set `dtls_expected_peer_handshake_number` to `dtls_peer_handshake_number + 1` before the existing handshake-completion reset logic, then run duplicate Finished, retransmitted Finished, last-flight retransmission, and renegotiation tests.
